SIMPLE: materialize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Materialize
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Materialized</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Materializing</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>mat⟦eacute⟧rialiser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To invest with
material characteristics; to make perceptible to the senses; hence, to
present to the mind through the medium of material objects.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Having with wonderful art and beauty <qex>materialized</qex>, if I
may so call it, a scheme of abstracted notions, and clothed the most
nice, refined conceptions of philosophy in sensible images.</q>
<rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To regard as matter; to consider or explain by the
laws or principles which are appropriate to matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to assume a character appropriate to
material things; to occupy with material interests; <as>as, to
<ex>materialize</ex> thought</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Spiritualism)</fld> <def>To make visible in, or as
in, a material form; -- said of spirits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A female spirit form temporarily <qex>materialized</qex>, and not
distinguishable from a human being.</q> <rj><qau>Epes
Sargent.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Materialize
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To appear as
a material form; to take substantial shape.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come into existence; <as>as, the promised
donations never <ex>materialized</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materially</ent>⟦br⟧
